ML detector-evaluation metric reference
=======================================

eval_reference.txt holds ROC/AUC/confusion-matrix metrics (AUC, and per-
threshold TP/FP/TN/FN with P_d/P_md/P_fa/precision/accuracy/F1) for a range of
(label, score) datasets, computed by an independent third-party authority and
used to externally validate Kshana's detector-agnostic evaluation testbed
(`impairment_eval`; see tests/eval_metrics_reference.rs). These files are not
part of the Kshana source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages —
they exist only for the test suite.

Oracle
------
scikit-learn 1.9.0 — the de-facto reference implementation of classification
metrics (Pedregosa et al., "Scikit-learn: Machine Learning in Python", JMLR 12,
2011; open source, BSD). The evaluation metrics are deterministic functions of
(labels, scores), so matching scikit-learn's numbers for identical data is a
genuine *external* cross-check of Kshana's metric maths — the same kind of
validation DOP gets against gnss_lib_py and the reference frames against ERFA.
This validates the *metric engine* (what `impairment_eval` computes), not the
synthetic impairment corpus (which is parameter-grounded, not field/IQ, and is
honestly labelled MODELLED, not externally validated).

Conventions (matched exactly to impairment_eval)
------------------------------------------------
* AUC = Mann-Whitney U with ties counted ½  ==  sklearn roc_auc_score.
* Predict positive iff score >= threshold     ==  numpy scores >= t.
* Ratios use zero-division → 0                ==  sklearn zero_division=0.
Scores and thresholds are emitted with Python repr so the Rust test parses the
identical f64; the per-threshold confusion counts therefore agree exactly
(integer match), and the derived ratios / AUC agree to < 1e-9.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_eval_reference.py (scikit-learn 1.9.0 +
numpy, under Python 3.11). The datasets span perfect separation (AUC 1.0),
overlapping Gaussians, heavy ties, class imbalance, and an inverted/worse-than-
chance ranking (AUC 0.0), with thresholds including predict-all, predict-none,
exact score values (>= boundary) and the median.

Format
------
'#'-prefixed comments, then one block per dataset:
  DATASET <name>
  L <comma-separated 0/1 labels>
  S <comma-separated f64 scores (repr)>
  AUC <f64>
  THR <threshold> <tp> <fp> <tn> <fn> <pd> <pmd> <pfa> <precision> <accuracy> <f1>
  ... (one THR line per threshold)
  END
